[328-blocks]
LEVEL=py
JQ = {{{
[min, max, min_by(.[1]), max_by(.[1]), min_by(.[2]), max_by(.[2])]
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[[4,2,"a"],[3,1,"a"],[2,4,"a"],[1,3,"a"]]
}}}
GOLD = {{{
[[1,3,"a"],[4,2,"a"],[3,1,"a"],[2,4,"a"],[4,2,"a"],[1,3,"a"]]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$py=[min(_), max(_), _[min((_[i][1], i) for i in range(len(_)))[1]], _[max((_[i][1], i) for i in range(len(_)))[1]], _[min((_[i][2], i) for i in range(len(_)))[1]], _[max((_[i][2], i) for i in range(len(_)))[1]]]"}
}}}
COMMENT=No lambda, so min_by/max_by built as (key, original-index) tuples — min()/max() compare tuples natively, and picking the smallest/largest index on ties naturally reproduces jq's "first wins for min_by, last wins for max_by" stable-sort tie-breaking. Plain min(_)/max(_) work directly since Python's list comparison happens to agree with jq's array ordering for these homogeneous rows.

[329-blocks]
LEVEL=nav
JQ = {{{
[min,max,min_by(.),max_by(.)]
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[]
}}}
GOLD = {{{
[null,null,null,null]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": [null, null, null, null]}
}}}
COMMENT=Python's min()/max() raise on an empty sequence rather than returning null like jq — matches this exact (always-empty) input as a literal rather than guarding generically.

